\description{
Computes each respondent's \strong{personal reliability}. Within each scale block
(given by \code{items$scale}) the items are split into two halves; the mean of each
half is formed, the two half-mean vectors are correlated across scale blocks,
Spearman-Brown corrected (\verb{2r / (1 + r)}, clamped at \code{-1}), and \strong{negated}. A
careful respondent answers the two halves of each scale consistently, so the
halves correlate highly and the negated score is low; a careless respondent's
halves decouple, so the score is high. \strong{High} values therefore flag
carelessness.
}
\details{
Two variants share this definition and differ only in how each scale is
halved:
\itemize{
\item \strong{PR} (Jackson, 1976; \code{resample = FALSE}) uses a single deterministic
split: the first half of each scale's items against the second half.
\item \strong{RPR} (Goldammer et al., 2024; \code{resample = TRUE}, the default) averages
the statistic over \code{n_resamples} \strong{random} within-scale splits. Resampling
removes the arbitrariness of a single fixed split and is the recommended
reliability index.
}

\strong{Reproducibility (RPR).} RPR draws random splits, so its result depends on
the random-number stream. With the default \code{seed = NULL} the ambient session
RNG is used and \strong{repeated calls give different scores}; pass an integer
\code{seed} to make a run reproducible. A non-\code{NULL} \code{seed} is applied locally and
the previous RNG state is restored on return, so a seeded call reproduces
\strong{without} disturbing the caller's random stream. PR (\code{resample = FALSE}) is
deterministic and ignores \code{seed} and \code{n_resamples}.

\strong{Reverse-keying.} Reverse-keyed items (\code{items$reverse_keyed}) are
reverse-scored with the self-inverse reflection \code{(min + max) - x} (with \code{max}
the largest response option, \code{items$max}) \emph{before} the half-means are formed,
so the index always sees trait-aligned responses. The scale base \code{min}
defaults to \code{1} (the \verb{1..max} coding), giving the classic \code{(max + 1) - x};
declare \code{items$min} for a 0-based or bipolar scale. Supply the raw responses
and declare reverse items through \code{items}; pre-scoring them and leaving
\code{reverse_keyed = FALSE} yields the same result.

\strong{Cutoff.} The default flags the lowest-reliability respondents: the cutoff
is the empirical \code{1 - fpr} quantile of the observed scores (the 95th
percentile by default) and respondents at or above it are flagged. This is a
\strong{ranking} convention -- a sample percentile flags \strong{at least} \code{fpr} of
respondents (more when scores tie at the cutoff) -- not a calibrated
false-positive rate. Adjust the target tail
with \code{fpr}, or pass an absolute \code{cutoff} in \verb{[-1, 1]} to flag on a literal
score threshold (e.g. one carried over from a calibration sample). \code{fpr} and
\code{cutoff} are mutually exclusive.

\strong{Abstention.} A respondent for whom fewer than two scale blocks yield a
finite half-mean pair, or whose half-mean vectors have no variance across
scales, has no defined reliability correlation: both \code{value} and \code{flagged} are
\code{NA} and the row is excluded from the flag count and rate. A scale with only
one item cannot be split and is skipped. For RPR a respondent is \code{NA} only
when \strong{every} resampled iteration abstains; otherwise the score averages the
finite iterations.
}
\section{What this catches}{

Random, alternating, and opposite-pattern responding whose within-scale halves
diverge. On a forward-keyed (or scale-midpoint) battery it \strong{misses} pure
straightlining and midpoint locking -- the constant row's half-means are
identical, so it abstains -- so straightlining is best caught directly with
\code{\link[=cier_longstring]{cier_longstring()}} and \code{\link[=cier_irv]{cier_irv()}}.
}

